        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>Do leap years affect manual age calculation?</h3>
            <p>Yes. If you are calculating the exact number of accumulated days lived rather than just 'Years/Months/Days', every leap year you have lived through adds one exact day to your chronological lifespan.</p>
            
            <h3>What is the difference between chronological age and biological age?</h3>
            <p>Chronological age is the exact literal time that has passed from your date of birth. Biological age is a scientific term used to describe how old your cells and organs appear to be based on lifestyle, diet, and DNA damage compared to average population metrics.</p>
            
            <h3>Why is my age calculated differently in different countries?</h3>
            <p>Most of the Western world calculates age starting at 0 on the day of birth, turning 1 on the first anniversary. However, in certain traditional East Asian age reckoning systems, a baby is considered 1 year old on the day of birth, and adds a year every New Year's Day.</p>
        </div>

